I know you're looking for vet advice here but I think you should take him to get checked out. Our male cat started peeing outside of the box and testing revealed struvite crystals as the cause, meaning they weren't getting enough water. We always knew they loved drinking water from cups left on the coffee table so we purposely put out a cup of water for them, which lead to leaving a tupperware bowl for them, to now having a giant glass bowl of water for the cats on our coffee table. Could be anecdotal but he hasn't had an issue in over a year.

Diagnosed at 33. The drugs are awesome and do exactly what they should, however, I don' take them because while my ADHD is a mild hindrance to my life I enjoy my brain as-is. It sucks for when I need to study or when someone is telling me something important, but the other 99% of the time it's like a fucking constant stimulus-seeking fest and it makes me funny and personable.

I was taking 50mg of Vyvanse and it made me a fucking mute. I hated it. I did try taking the capsule apart and taking less of the meds, which did help, but honestly it still has such an impact on my personality I'd rather just deal with having to use other techniques to study. It helps that the education I'm getting now is a specific medical career that I find infinitely fascinating so the ADHD isn't too bad. Just takes me a while to get settled. I still re-read things several times before it sinks it but whatever.

Many years ago my dad gave my dog a t-bone steak bone (cooked) as we'd always done. At 4am she woke me up puking. Then again at 5, 6, and 7am. I thought she was just sick so when I took her outside at 7 to pee I googled it and it basically said "TAKE YOUR DOG TO THE VET IDIOT" so I did. X-rays showed she had a giant, triangular piece of bone shard stuck in her stomach. Vet suggested I feed her cotton balls to wrap around the bone so she could pass it. Easier said than done, but it must've worked because she's still alive 9 years later.
